{
  "items": [
    {
      "prompt": "A metal strip is dipped into a copper(II) sulfate solution and turns blue with solid deposits forming on it.\n\nWrite the half-reaction occurring at this surface, identifying whether oxidation or reduction takes place. Explain your reasoning by tracking electron movement direction.",
      "answer": "The process is reduction: Cu²⁺(aq) + 2e⁻ → Cu(s). Electrons flow from Zn (oxidized) to copper ions; since electrons are gained in this step, it must be reduction, not oxidation despite the metal appearance change which confuses the direction.",
      "rubric": "- Correct half-reaction equation with states\n- Explicitly identifies 'reduction' and correctly tracks electron gain",
      "skill": "apply"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "Consider a galvanic cell where zinc acts as the anode. Based on standard potentials, predict which species gains electrons in the cathode compartment.\n\nFormulate the reduction half-reaction for that species and state why this process corresponds to electron gain rather than loss.",
      "answer": "Copper ions (Cu²⁺) are reduced: Cu²⁺(aq) + 2e⁻ → Cu(s). Zinc loses electrons (oxidized), forcing them into the external circuit toward copper. The species gaining those electrons undergoes reduction because electron addition defines that definition.",
      "rubric": "- Identifies correct cathode reactant (Cu²⁺)\n- Uses 'reduction' correctly linked to electron gain concept",
      "skill": "produce"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "A student claims: \"In this reaction, electrons move from the element with higher electronegativity to lower electronegativity.\"\n\nCritique this statement using a specific redox example (e.g., Zn/Cu). Correct their directional reasoning regarding electron source and sink.",
      "answer": "The direction is reversed. Electrons flow from Zinc (lower EN, oxidized) to Copper ions (higher EN context, reduced), not the other way around. Oxidation occurs at the lower electronegativity site where electrons originate; reduction happens at higher potential sites accepting them.",
      "rubric": "- Identifies error in electron direction\n- Cites correct flow: Low EN → High EN (or Zn to Cu)",
      "skill": "critique"
    }
  ],
  "note": null,
  "intervention": null
}

