    {
      "prompt": "Your tomato plants show yellowing leaves and stunted growth in hot weather, but soil pH remains optimal at 6.2. You need to choose a nitrogen amendment that won't acidify the soil or attract pests while supporting rapid foliage recovery. Which organic source is most appropriate among compost tea, fish emulsion, and blood meal? Justify your choice based on nutrient profile and plant response.",
      "answer": "Compost tea (or well-aged manure liquid) is best because it provides a balanced N-P-K release without the high salt content or acidification risk of fresh blood meal. Fish emulsion can also work but may introduce nitrogen spikes if not aged; composted products offer sustained, less shocking nutrition for established plants.",
      "rubric": "- Identifies an organic liquid amendment as primary choice\n- Explains why it avoids soil acidification and pest attraction",
    },
    {
      "prompt": "You notice white powdery patches on your basil's undersides along with slowed growth. Your initial assumption is nitrogen deficiency, but recent lab tests show adequate nitrate levels despite the foliar symptoms. Design an NPK-adjusted soil amendment plan that addresses this specific symptom while maintaining proper K for pest resistance.",
      "answer": "Shift focus from general N to Phosphorus and Potassium deficiencies; white powdery spots often signal fungal issues exacerbated by poor air circulation or excess phosphorus, but the slowed growth suggests a need for balanced micronutrients. Add composted pine bark fines with bone meal (P) rather than straight nitrogen sources to avoid fueling mildew while aiding root strength.",
      "rubric": "- Rejects N-deficiency diagnosis in favor of P/K/micronutrient support\n- Proposes phosphate/bone meal amendment instead of nitrogen fertilizer",
    },
    {
      "prompt": "In preparation for your late summer squash harvest, you observe pale green new leaves on vigorous vines. The plants are watered frequently but show no signs of drought stress or nutrient burn at the edges. Which specific macro-nutrient is likely limiting your yield potential in this high-volume growth phase?",
      "answer": "Potassium (K) deficiency is most likely, indicated by pale green young leaves and reduced yield capacity despite adequate water; K regulates turgor pressure and carbohydrate translocation to developing fruits.",
      "rubric": "- Identifies potassium as the limiting macro-nutrient",
    }
  ],
  "note": null,
  "intervention": null
}

